Utility</strong>. In the essay, he focused on Social Capital and Utility.&n=
bsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 1em 0;">Utility is relatively easy to understand. If you can find =
the answer to your question on Quora or easily reach an old high school fri=
end whose number you lost on Facebook, those products are providing you uti=
lity.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Social capital, on the other hand, is harder to def=
ine and relies on the creation of a &#8220;successful status game.&#8221; T=
o help explain why some new social networks succeed and others fail, he use=
d a metaphor: crypto.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">He said that new social networks ar=
e analogous to Initial Coin Offerings (ICOs) in four ways:&nbsp;</p><ol sty=
le=3D"margin: 1em 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-speci=
al-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0;"><em>Each new social network issues a new form of socia=
